/prof/details/page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=CMACA&Code1=933&Geo2=PR&Code2=59&SearchText=vancouver&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&B1=Language&TABID=1&type=0 Census Profile, 2016 Census: Greater Vancouver, Regional district]. Statistics Canada. Retrieved 30 March 2020.</ref>\n|-\n!#\n!Language\n!Population\n!Percent\n|-\n|1\n|[[English language|English]]\n|1,316,635\n|58.08%\n|-\n|2\n|[[Cantonese language|Cantonese]]\n|185,140\n|6.99%\n|-\n|3\n|[[Punjabi language|Punjabi]]\n|182,050\n|6.88%\n|-\n|4\n|[[Mandarin language|Mandarin]]\n|176,435\n|6.66%\n|-\n|5\n|[[Tagalog language|Tagalog (Filipino)]]\n|68,245\n|2.58%\n|-\n|6\n|[[Korean language|Korean]]\n|47,715\n|1.80%\n|-\n|7\n|[[Persian language|Persian]]\n|41,645\n|1.57%\n|-\n|8\n|[[Spanish language|Spanish]]\n|38,705\n|1.46%\n|-\n|9\n|[[German language|German]]\n|32,215\n|1.22%\n|-\n|10\n|[[French language|French]]\n|27,815\n|1.05%\n|-\n|}\n\n===Religion===\nThe Lower Mainland includes large Christian, Irreligious, Sikh and Buddhist communities. The Sikh population, numbering 185,000 or 7.2 percent of the total population, is significant across Metro Vancouver and the Fraser Valley; proportionally, it is more than five times higher than the national average of 1.4 percent.\n{{Bar box|bars={{bar percent|[[Christianity|Christian]]|#ff4d4d|42.6}} {{bar percent|[[Irreligion|Irreligious/Other]]|#cc33ff|41.6}} {{bar percent|[[Sikhism|Sikh]]|orange|7.2}} {{bar percent|[[Buddhism|Buddhist]]|yellow|3.1}} {{bar percent|[[Islam|Muslim]]|#33cc33|2.9}} {{bar percent|[[Hinduism|Hindu]]|gold|1.7}} {{bar percent|[[Jewish]]|Blue|0.7}} {{bar percent|Aboriginal|grey|0.1}}|left1=Religion|right1=Percent(%)|title=Religion in the Lower Mainland (2011 census)<ref>[https://www12.statcan.gc.ca/nhs-enm/2011/dp-pd/prof/details/page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=CD&Code1=5909&Data=Count&SearchText=fraser%20valley&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&A1=Religion&B1=All&Custom=&amp;TABID=1 NHS Profile, Fraser Valley, RD, British Columbia, 2011]. Statistics Canada. Retrieved 30 March 2020.</ref><ref>[https://www12.statcan.gc.ca/nhs-enm/2011/dp-pd/prof/details/page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=CMA&Code1=933&Data=Count&SearchText=vancouver&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&A1=Religion&B1=All&Custom=&amp;TABID=1 NHS Profile, Vancouver, CMA, British Columbia, 2011]. Statistics Canada. Retrieved 30 March 2020.</ref>}}\n\n==Regional districts==\nRegional districts were first created across British Columbia in 1966\u20131967 to form bodies for inter-municipal coordination and to extend municipal-level powers to areas outside existing municipalities. Today, the Lower Mainland includes two [[List of British Columbia Regional Districts|regional districts]]: the [[Metro Vancouver Regional District]] (MVRD) and the [[Fraser Valley Regional District, British Columbia|Fraser Valley Regional District]] (FVRD). Both regional districts, however, include areas outside the traditional limits of the Lower Mainland. Metro Vancouver includes areas like Surrey and Langley that are geographically in the [[Fraser Valley]].\n\nThe Metro Vancouver Regional District is made up of 21 municipalities. The MVRD is bordered on the west by the Strait of Georgia, to the north by the [[Squamish-Lillooet Regional District]], on the east by the Fraser Valley Regional District, and to the south by [[Whatcom County, Washington]], in the [[United States]].\n\nThe Fraser Valley Regional District lies east of the Greater Vancouver Regional District, and comprises the cities of [[Abbotsford, British Columbia|Abbotsford]] and [[Chilliwack]], the [[District municipality|district municipalities]] of [[Mission, British Columbia|Mission]], [[Agassiz, British Columbia|Kent]], and [[Hope, British Columbia|Hope]], and the village of [[Harrison Hot Springs, British Columbia|Harrison Hot Springs]]. It also includes many unincorporated areas in the Fraser Valley and along the west side of the [[Fraser Canyon]] (the Fraser Canyon is not in the Lower Mainland).\n\nRegional district powers are very limited and other localized provincial government services are delivered through other regionalization systems.\n\n==Indigenous territories==\nThe traditional territories of the [[Musqueam]] and [[Tsleil-Waututh First Nation|Tsleil'waututh]] lie completely within the region; the southern portion of [[Squamish people|Squamish]] traditional territory is also in the region. Its claims overlap those of the Tsleil-waututh, Musqueam, and Kwikwetlem. Other peoples whose territories lie within the region are the [[Sto:lo]], [[Sts'Ailes|Chehalis]], [[Katzie First Nation|Katzie]], [[Kwantlen First Nation|Kwantlen]], [[Tsawwassen First Nation|Tsawwassen]], and [[Semiahmoo First Nation|Semiahmoo]]; many of their territories overlap with those of the Musqueam, and with each other. Many other peoples of the [[Georgia Strait]] region also frequented the lower Fraser, including those from Vancouver Island and what is now [[Whatcom County, Washington]].\n\nSto:lo traditional territory, known as ''Solh Temexw'' in [[Halkomelem]], more or less coincides with the traditional conception of the Lower Mainland, except for the inclusion of [[Port Douglas, British Columbia|Port Douglas]] at the head of Harrison Lake, which is in [[In-SHUCK-ch]] territory, and the lands around Burrard Inlet.\n\n==Health regions==\nHealth system services and governance in the Lower Mainland are provided by [[Vancouver Coastal Health]], serving Vancouver, Richmond and the North Shore, and the mainland coast as far north as the [[Coast of British Columbia|Central Coast]] region, and [[Fraser Health]], which serves the area of the Lower Mainland east of Vancouver and Richmond.<ref>BC Ministry of Health. [http://www.health.gov.bc.ca/socsec/provmap.html British Columbia Health Authorities: Maps] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110705014605/http://www.health.gov.bc.ca/socsec/provmap.html |date=5 July 2011 }}. Retrieved on: 2011-07-10.</ref>\n\n==Natural threats==\n\n===Flooding===\nThe Lower Mainland is considered to have a high vulnerability to flood risk. There have been two major floods, the largest in 1894 and the second largest in 1948. According to the Fraser Basin Council, scientists predict a one-in-three chance of a similar-sized flood occurring in the next 50 years.<ref>{{cite web\n |title       = Flood Hazard Management on the Fraser River\n |publisher   = Fraser Basin Council\n |url         = http://www.fraserbasin.bc.ca/programs/flood.html#risk\n |accessdate  = 2008-06-18\n |url-status  = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20080626142044/http://www.fraserbasin.bc.ca/programs/flood.html#risk\n |archivedate = 26 June 2008\n |df          = dmy-all\n}}</ref>\n\nIn the spring of 2007, the Lower Mainland was on high alert for flooding. Higher than normal snow packs in the [[British Columbia Interior]] prompted municipal governments to start taking emergency measures in the region. [[Dike (construction)|Dikes]] along the [[Fraser River]] are regulated to handle about 8.5 m at the Mission Gauge (the height above sea level of the dykes at Mission). Warmer than normal weather in the interior caused large amounts of snow to melt prematurely, resulting in higher than normal water levels, which, nevertheless, remained well below flood levels.<ref>\n{{cite news\n |title       = Fraser Valley prepares for possible flooding\n |publisher   = CBC News\n |date        = 5 June 2007\n |url         = https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/fraser-valley-prepares-for-possible-flooding-1.648037\n |accessdate  = 2007-06-24\n |url-status     = live\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20070709215645/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/fraser-valley-prepares-for-possible-flooding-1.648037\n |archivedate = 9 July 2007\n |df          = dmy-all\n}}</ref><ref>Nguyen, Linda (7 June 2007). [http://www.canada.com/vancouversun/story.html?id=570b533b-65a6-438c-813a-04f5a4c4ec89 Lower Mainland at flood risk for weeks yet] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070626080216/http://www.canada.com/vancouversun/story.html?id=570b533b-65a6-438c-813a-04f5a4c4ec89 |date=26 June 2007 }}. ''Vancouver Sun.'' Retrieved on: 18 June 2008.</ref>\n\nFlooding can cover much of the Lower Mainland. [[Cloverdale, British Columbia|Cloverdale]], [[Barnston Island]], low-lying areas of [[Maple Ridge, British Columbia|Maple Ridge]], areas west of [[Hope, British Columbia|Hope]], [[White Rock, British Columbia|White Rock]], [[Richmond, British Columbia|Richmond]], parts of [[Vancouver]], and parts of [[Surrey, British Columbia|Surrey]] are potentially at risk. In 2007, the Lower Mainland was largely spared, although northern regions of the province, along the [[Skeena River|Skeena]] and [[Nechako River|Nechako]] Rivers, experienced floods. [[Climate science|Climate scientists]] predict that increasing temperatures will mean wetter winters and more snow at the high elevations. This will increase the likelihood of snowmelt floods.<ref>\n{{cite news\n  | last = Drake\n  | first = Laura\n  | title = Flooding in future may be more frequent, scientists say\n  | newspaper = Globe and Mail\n  | date = 16 June 2007\n  | url = https://www.theglobeandmail.com/servlet/story/LAC.20070616.BCFLOOD16/TPStory/TPNational/BritishColumbia/\n  | accessdate = 2007-06-24 }}</ref>\n\nThe provincial government maintains an integrated flood hazard management program and extensive flood protection infrastructure in the Lower Mainland. The infrastructure consists of dikes, [[pump station]]s, floodboxes, [[riprap]], and [[relief well]]s.<ref>{{cite web\n |author      = Ministry of Environment\n |title       = Lower Mainland Dike and Emergency Maps\n |url         = http://www.env.gov.bc.ca/wsd/public_safety/flood/maps.html#emergmaps\n |accessdate  = 2007-06-24\n |url-status  = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20070620191654/http://www.env.gov.bc.ca/wsd/public_safety/flood/maps.html#emergmaps\n |archivedate = 20 June 2007\n |df          = dmy-all\n}}</ref>\n\n===Earthquakes===\nWhile [[earthquake]]s are common in British Columbia and adjacent coastal waters, most are minor in energy release or are sufficiently remote to have little effect on populated areas. Nevertheless, earthquakes with a magnitude of up to 7.3 have occurred within {{Convert|150|km||abbr=}} of the Lower Mainland.\n\nBased on geological evidence, however, stronger earthquakes appear to have occurred at approximately 600-year intervals. Therefore, there is a probability that there will be a major earthquake in the region within the next 200 years.<ref name=eqplan>British Columbia.  Provincial Emergency Program. (1999). [http://www.pep.bc.ca/hazard_plans/eqplan99/eqplan99-x2.html British Columbia Earthquake Response Plan, Appendix 2-The Earthquake Threat] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081113110254/http://www.pep.bc.ca/hazard_plans/eqplan99/eqplan99-x2.html |date=13 November 2008 }}. {{ISBN|0-7726-3924-8}}. Retrieved on: 7 April 2008.</ref>\n\nIn April 2008, the [[United States Geological Survey]] released information concerning a newly found [[Fault (geology)|fault]] south of downtown [[Abbotsford, British Columbia|Abbotsford]], called the Boulder Creek Fault. Scientists now believe this fault is [[Active fault|active]] and capable of producing earthquakes in the 6.8 magnitude range.<ref>[https://archive.is/20120903164840/http://www.mcclatchydc.com/science/v-print/story/34512.html McClatchy Washington Bureau]. Earthquake risk. Retrieved on 2009-05-12.</ref>\n\n===Volcanoes===\nMuch of the Lower Mainland is vulnerable to [[explosive eruption]]s from the [[Garibaldi Volcanic Belt]]. Volcanoes in this zone are capable of producing large quantities of [[volcanic ash]] that may cause short and long term water supply problems for Lower Mainland communities.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=[[Natural Resources Canada]] |url=http://gsc.nrcan.gc.ca/volcanoes/cat/feature_garibaldi_e.php |title=Garibaldi volcanic belt: Garibaldi Lake volcanic field |work=Catalogue of Canadian volcanoes |date=2009-04-01 |accessdate=2018-05-26 |url-status=unfit |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080513070258/http://gsc.nrcan.gc.ca/volcanoes/cat/feature_garibaldi_e.php |archivedate=May 13, 2008 }}</ref> All airports covered by the accompanying [[eruption column]] would be closed, heavy [[pyroclastic fall|ash falls]] would damage electrical equipment and weak structures could collapse under the weight of the ash.<ref>{{cite |last=V. Stasiuk|first=Mark|last2=J. Hickson|first2=Catherine|last3=Mulder|first3=Taimi|journal=Natural Hazards|title=The Vulnerability of Canada to Volcanic Hazards|publisher=[[Kluwer Academic Publishers]]|volume=28|page=580|year=2003|issn=0921-030X}}</ref>\n\n==Communities==\nThe Lower Mainland's communities includes large cities in Metro Vancouver, and smaller cities, towns and villages along both banks of the Fraser River. Neighbourhoods within cities are not listed unless historically or otherwise notable and/or separate.  Only some of the many Indian Reserves are listed.\n\n; Upper Fraser Valley\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n* [[Agassiz, British Columbia|Agassiz]]\n* [[Bridal Falls, British Columbia|Bridal Falls]]\n* [[Chehalis, British Columbia|Chehalis]]\n* [[Chilliwack]]\n* [[Cultus Lake, British Columbia|Cultus Lake]]\n* [[Greendale, British Columbia|Greendale]]\n* [[Lake Errock, British Columbia|Lake Errock]]\n* [[Kent, British Columbia|Kent]]\n* [[Harrison Hot Springs, British Columbia|Harrison Hot Springs]]\n* [[Harrison Mills, British Columbia|Harrison Mills]]\n* [[Hope, British Columbia|Hope]]\n* [[Flood, British Columbia|Flood]]\n* [[Laidlaw, British Columbia|Laidlaw]]\n* [[Popkum, British Columbia|Popkum]]\n* [[Rosedale, British Columbia|Rosedale]]\n* [[Ruby Creek, British Columbia|Ruby Creek]]\n* [[Sardis, British Columbia|Sardis]]\n* [[Yarrow, British Columbia|Yarrow]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n; Central Fraser Valley\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n* [[Abbotsford, British Columbia|Abbotsford]]\n* [[Aldergrove, British Columbia|Aldergrove]]\n* [[Bradner, British Columbia|Bradner]]\n* [[Clayburn, British Columbia|Clayburn]]\n* [[Clearbrook, British Columbia|Clearbrook]]\n* [[Deroche, British Columbia|Deroche]]\n* [[Dewdney, British Columbia|Dewdney]]\n* [[Durieu, British Columbia|Durieu]]\n* [[Hatzic, British Columbia|Hatzic]]\n* [[Huntingdon, British Columbia|Huntingdon]]\n* [[Matsqui, British Columbia|Matsqui]]\n* [[Mission, British Columbia|Mission]]\n* [[Mount Lehman, British Columbia|Mount Lehman]]\n* [[Nicomen Island]]\n* [[Ruskin, British Columbia|Ruskin]]\n* [[Silverdale, British Columbia|Silverdale]]\n* [[Silverhill, British Columbia|Silverhill]]\n* [[Squamish, British Columbia|Squamish]]\n* [[Stave Falls]]\n* [[Steelhead, British Columbia|Steelhead]]\n* [[Sumas, British Columbia|Sumas]] (Sumas Prairie)\n* [[Whonnock, British Columbia|Whonnock]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n; Lower Fraser Valley/Metro Vancouver\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n* [[Albion, British Columbia|Albion]]\n* [[Anmore, British Columbia|Anmore]]\n* [[Annieville, British Columbia|Annieville]]\n* [[Barnston Island]]\n* [[Belcarra]]\n* [[Boundary Bay, British Columbia|Boundary Bay]]\n* [[Bridgeport, British Columbia|Bridgeport]]\n* [[Brighouse, British Columbia|Brighouse]]\n* [[Burnaby]]\n* [[Burquitlam, British Columbia|Burquitlam]]\n* [[Cloverdale, British Columbia|Cloverdale]]\n* [[Coquitlam]]\n* [[Crescent Beach, British Columbia|Crescent Beach]]\n* [[Derby, British Columbia|Derby]] (\"Old Derby\")\n* [[Douglas, British Columbia|Douglas]]\n* [[Delta, British Columbia|Delta]]\n* [[Fort Langley, British Columbia|Fort Langley]]\n* [[Haney, British Columbia|Haney]]\n* [[Kanaka Creek, British Columbia|Kanaka Creek]]\n* [[Langley, British Columbia (city)|Langley City]]\n* [[Langley, British Columbia (district municipality)|Langley District]]\n* [[Lions Bay, British Columbia|Lions Bay]]\n* [[Maillardville, British Columbia|Maillardville]]\n* [[Maple Ridge, British Columbia|Maple Ridge]]\n* [[New Westminster]]\n* [[Newton, British Columbia|Newton]]\n* [[North Vancouver (city)|North Vancouver City]]\n* [[North Vancouver (district municipality)|North Vancouver District]]\n* [[Pitt Meadows]]\n* [[Port Coquitlam]]\n* [[Port Hammond, British Columbia|Port Hammond]] (Hammond)\n* [[Port Kells]]\n* [[Port Moody]]\n* [[Queensborough, British Columbia|Queensborough]]\n* [[Richmond, British Columbia|Richmond]]\n* [[Sapperton, New Westminster|Sapperton]]\n* [[Scottsdale, British Columbia|Scottsdale]]\n* [[Steveston, British Columbia|Steveston]]\n* [[Surrey, British Columbia|Surrey]]\n* [[Tsawwassen, British Columbia|Tsawwassen]]\n* [[Vancouver]]\n* [[West Vancouver]]\n* [[Whalley, British Columbia|Whalley]]\n* [[White Rock, British Columbia|White Rock]]\n* [[Yennadon, British Columbia|Yennadon]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Fraser Lowland]]\n* [[List of provincial parks of the Lower Mainland]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{wikivoyage-inline|Lower Mainland}}\n\n{{Subdivisions of British Columbia|regions=yes}}\n\n[[Category:Lower Mainland| ]]\n[[Category:South Coast of British Columbia]]\n[[Category:Geography of Vancouver]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use Canadian English|date=March 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2015}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n<!--See Template:Infobox Settlement for additional fields that may be available-->\n<!--See the Table at Infobox Settlement for all fields and descriptions of usage-->\n<!-- Basic info  ---------------->\n|official_name          = Lower Mainland\n|nickname               = \n|settlement_type        = Economic region\n<!-- images and maps  ----------->\n|image_map              = LowerMainland.jpg\n|mapsize                = 300px\n|map_caption            = Core area of the Lower Mainland outlined\n<!-- Location ------------------>\n|subdivision_type       = Country\n|subdivision_name       = [[Canada]]\n|subdivision_type1      = Province\n|subdivision_name1      = [[British Columbia]]\n<!-- Area    --------------------->\n|area_magnitude         = \n|unit_pref                = <!--Enter: Imperial, if Imperial (metric) is desired-->\n|area_footnotes           =\n|area_total_km2           = 36303.31\n|area_total_sq_mi         =\n|area_blank1_title        = Extended area\n|area_blank1_km2          = 31368.24\n|area_blank1_sq_mi        =\n|area_blank2_title        = Core area\n|area_blank2_km2          = 4935.07\n|area_blank2_sq_mi        = \n<!-- Population   ----------------------->\n|population_as_of               = [[Canada 2016 Census|2016]]<!-- Do not change until the 2021 census is released -->\n|population_footnotes           =\n|population_note                =\n|population_total               = 2832000<!-- Do not change until the 2021 census is released -->\n|population_density_km2         = 78.0<!-- Do not change until the 2021 census is released -->\n|population_blank1_title        = Extended area\n|population_blank1              = 86539<!-- Do not change until the 2021 census is released -->\n|population_blank2_title        = Core area\n|population_blank2              = 2745461<!-- Do not change until the 2021 census is released -->\n\n<!-- General information  --------------->\n|timezone               = [[Pacific Time Zone|PST]]\n|utc_offset             = \u22128\n|timezone_DST           = PDT\n|utc_offset_DST         = \u22127\n|coordinates            = {{coord|49|05|00|N|122|21|00|W|region:CA-BC|display=inline,title}}\n|postal_code_type       = Postal code prefixes\n|postal_code            = [[List of V postal codes of Canada|V]]\n|area_codes              = [[Area code 236|236]], [[Area code 604|604]], [[Area code 672|672]], [[Area code 778|778]]\n}}\nThe '''Lower Mainland''' is a name commonly applied to the region surrounding and including [[Vancouver]], British Columbia, Canada. As of 2016, 2,832,000 people (60 percent of British Columbia's total population) lived in the region; sixteen of the province's thirty most populous municipalities are located there.<ref name=2016census>Canada 2016 Census [http://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2016/dp-pd/prof/details/Page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=ER&Code1=5920&Geo2=PR&Code2=59&Data=Count&SearchText=British%20Columbia&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&B1=All&GeoLevel=PR&GeoCode=59 Canada 2016 Census] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170211082223/http://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2016/dp-pd/prof/details/Page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=ER&Code1=5920&Geo2=PR&Code2=59&Data=Count&SearchText=British%20Columbia&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&B1=All&GeoLevel=PR&GeoCode=59 |date=11 February 2017 }}. Retrieved on: 2017-02-10.</ref> Islands contained within rivers in the region are considered to be part of the Lower Mainland.\n\nWhile the term ''Lower Mainland'' has been recorded from the earliest period of non-native settlement in British Columbia, it has never been officially defined in legal terms. The [[British Columbia Geographical Names Information System]] (BCGNIS) comments that most residents of Vancouver might consider it to be only areas west of Mission and Abbotsford, while residents in the rest of the province consider it to be the whole region south of [[Whistler, British Columbia|Whistler]] and west of [[Hope, British Columbia|Hope]].<ref>{{Cite bcgnis|id=57400 |title=Lower Mainland}}</ref> However, the term has historically been in popular usage for over a century to describe a region that extends from [[Horseshoe Bay, British Columbia|Horseshoe Bay]] south to the [[Canada\u2013United States border]] and east to Hope at the eastern end of the [[Fraser Valley]].<ref>Gentilcore, R.L., ed. 1993. ''Historical Atlas of Canada, Vol II, The Land Transformed 1800\u20131891.'' Plate 36, \"Lower Mainland 1881.\" Toronto: University of Toronto Press. {{ISBN|0-8020-3447-0}}.</ref>\n\nThe climate, ecology and geology of the Lower Mainland are consistent enough that it has been classified as a separate ecoregion (the [[Lower Mainland Ecoregion]]) within the ecological framework of Canada, used by both the federal and provincial environment ministries.<ref name=PME>Environment Canada. [http://ecozones.ca/english/zone/PacificMaritime/ecoregions.html Pacific Maritime Ecozone] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111107191310/http://ecozones.ca/english/zone/PacificMaritime/ecoregions.html |date=7 November 2011 }}. Ecological Framework of Canada. Retrieved on: 2011-07-09.</ref><ref>{{cite web|publisher=BC Ministry of Environment|url=http://www.env.gov.bc.ca/ecology/ecoregions/humidtemp.html#georgia|title=Georgia Depression Ecoprovince|work=Ecoregions of British Columbia|accessdate=19 June 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080907191840/http://www.env.gov.bc.ca/ecology/ecoregions/humidtemp.html#georgia|archivedate=7 September 2008|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The region is the traditional territory of the [[Sto:lo people|Sto:lo]], a [[Halkomelem language|Halkomelem]]-speaking people of the [[Coast Salish peoples|Coast Salish]] linguistic and cultural grouping. There are two [[List of regional districts of British Columbia|regional districts]] within the region, [[Metro Vancouver Regional District|Metro Vancouver]] and the [[Fraser Valley Regional District|Fraser Valley]].\n\n==Geography==\n{{main|Lower Mainland Ecoregion}}\nThe region is bounded to the north by the [[Coast Mountains]] and to the southeast by the [[Cascade Range|Cascade Mountains]], and is traversed from east to west by the [[Fraser River]]. Due to its consistency of [[climate]], [[flora (plants)|flora]] and [[fauna (animals)|fauna]], [[geology]] and [[land use]], \"Lower Mainland\" is also the name of an [[ecoregion]]\u2014a biogeoclimatic region\u2014that comprises the eastern part of the [[Georgia Depression]] and extends from Powell River on the [[Sunshine Coast, British Columbia|Sunshine Coast]] to Hope at the eastern end of the Fraser Valley.<ref name=EC196>Environment Canada. [http://ecozones.ca/english/region/196.html Ecoregions of Canada \u2013 Lower Mainland] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130516091638/http://ecozones.ca/english/region/196.html |date=16 May 2013 }}. Ecological Framework of Canada. Retrieved on: 2011-07-09</ref>\n\nOne of the mildest climates in Canada, the region has a mean annual temperature of {{Convert|9|C||abbr=}} with a summer mean of {{Convert|15|C||abbr=}} and a winter mean of {{Convert|3.5|C||abbr=}}. Annual precipitation ranges from an annual mean of {{Convert|850|mm|in|abbr=}} in the west end to {{Convert|2000|mm|in|abbr=}} in the eastern end of the Fraser Valley and at higher elevations. Maximum precipitation occurs as rain in winter. Less than ten percent falls as snow at sea level but the amount of snowfall increases significantly with elevation.<ref name = EC196/>\n\n==Demographics==\n===Population===\n{{Historical populations\n| title = Population history\n| type  = Canada\n| align = right\n| footnote = ''Source: [[Statistics Canada]]''<br><ref>{{cite web|title=Community Highlights for Fraser Valley Regional District|url=https://www12.statcan.gc.ca/english/Profil01/CP01/Details/Page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=CD&Code1=5909&Geo2=PR&Code2=59&Data=Count&SearchText=fraser%20valley&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&B1=All&Custom=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title= Community Highlights for Vancouver|url=https://www12.statcan.gc.ca/english/profil01/CP01/Details/Page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=CMA&Code1=933__&Geo2=PR&Code2=59&Data=Count&SearchText=vancouver&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&B1=All&Custom=}}</ref><ref name=2011census>Canada 2011 Census [http://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2011/dp-pd/hlt-fst/pd-pl/Table-Tableau.cfm?LANG=Eng&T=311&SR=11&S=51&O=A&RPP=5&PR=59&CMA=0 Canada 2011 Census Subdivisions] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130923041559/http://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2011/dp-pd/hlt-fst/pd-pl/Table-Tableau.cfm?LANG=Eng&T=311&SR=11&S=51&O=A&RPP=5&PR=59&CMA=0 |date=23 September 2013 }}. Retrieved on: 2012-02-14.</ref><ref name=\"www5.statcan.gc.ca\">{{cite web |url=http://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2016/dp-pd/prof/details/page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=CD&Code1=5909&Geo2=PR&Code2=59&Data=Count&SearchText=fraser%20valley&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&B1=All&TABID=1 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2018-01-02 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170317054352/http://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2016/dp-pd/prof/details/page.cfm?Lang=E |archivedate=17 March 2017 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2016/dp-pd/prof/details/page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=CD&Code1=5915&Geo2=PR&Code2=59&Data=Count&SearchText=Greater%20Vancouver&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&B1=All&GeoLevel=PR&GeoCode=5915&TABID=1 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2018-01-07 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170719185845/http://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2016/dp-pd/prof/details/page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=CD&Code1=5915&Geo2=PR&Code2=59&Data=Count&SearchText=Greater%20Vancouver&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&B1=All&GeoLevel=PR&GeoCode=5915&TABID=1 |archivedate=19 July 2017 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n| 1986|1403044\n| 1991|1630104\n| [[Canada 1996 Census|1996]]|2054062\n| [[Canada 2001 Census|2001]]|2224515\n| [[Canada 2006 Census|2006]]|2373612\n| [[Canada 2011 Census|2011]]|2590921\n| [[Canada 2016 Census|2016]]|2759385\n}}\nAs of the 2016 census, the population of the Lower Mainland totals 2,759,385:\n* 295,934 in the [[Fraser Valley Regional District]]<ref name=\"www5.statcan.gc.ca\">{{cite web |url=http://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2016/dp-pd/prof/details/page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=CD&Code1=5909&Geo2=PR&Code2=59&Data=Count&SearchText=fraser%20valley&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&B1=All&TABID=1 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2018-01-02 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170317054352/http://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2016/dp-pd/prof/details/page.cfm?Lang=E |archivedate=17 March 2017 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n* 2,463,431 in [[Metro Vancouver Regional District|Metro Vancouver Regional district]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2016/dp-pd/prof/details/page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=CD&Code1=5915&Geo2=PR&Code2=59&Data=Count&SearchText=Greater%20Vancouver&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&B1=All&GeoLevel=PR&GeoCode=5915&TABID=1 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2018-01-07 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170719185845/http://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2016/dp-pd/prof/details/page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=CD&Code1=5915&Geo2=PR&Code2=59&Data=Count&SearchText=Greater%20Vancouver&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&B1=All&GeoLevel=PR&GeoCode=5915&TABID=1 |archivedate=19 July 2017 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nThese figures are slightly inflated due to the inclusion of areas within the Regional Districts which are not normally considered to be part of the Lower Mainland, notably the lower [[Fraser Canyon]] and the heads of [[Harrison Lake|Harrison]] and [[Pitt Lake]]s, which are within the [[Fraser Valley Regional District|FVRD]], and Lions Bay and Bowen Island, which are within the [[Metro Vancouver|Greater Vancouver Regional District]].\n\nThe population of the Lower Mainland was up 9.2 percent from the 2006 census. This is among the highest growth rates in the continent.\n\n===Ethnicity===\nThe Lower Mainland is among the most diverse regions in Canada. Europeans form a slight majority at 51.5 percent, followed by East Asians at 20.8 percent and South Asians at 12.2 percent.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! colspan=2 | [[Ethnic group]]s in the Lower Mainland (2016)<br><ref name=\"fraser-valley2016\">[https://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2016/dp-pd/prof/details/page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=CD&Code1=5909&Geo2=PR&Code2=59&Data=Count&SearchText=fraser%20valley&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&B1=All&TABID=1 Census Profile, 2016 Census: Fraser Valley, Regional district]. Statistics Canada. Retrieved 27 July 2018.</ref><ref name=\"vancouver-2016\">[http://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2016/dp-pd/prof/details/page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=CD&Code1=5915&Geo2=PR&Code2=59&Data=Count&SearchText=Greater%20Vancouver&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&B1=Visible%20minority&TABID=1 Census Profile, 2016 Census: Greater Vancouver, Regional district]. Statistics Canada. Retrieved 2 April 2018.</ref>!! Population !! %\n|-\n| rowspan=9 | [[Ethnic group]] || [[European Canadian|European]] || 1,397,280 || {{Percentage | 1397280 | 2715000 | 1}}\n|-\n| [[East Asia|East Asian]] || 564,445|| {{Percentage | 564445| 2715000 | 1}}\n|-\n| [[South Asian Canadians|South Asian]] || 330,925 || {{Percentage | 330925| 2715000 | 1}}\n|-\n| [[Southeast Asia]]n || 173,060|| {{Percentage | 173060| 2715000 | 1}}\n|-\n| [[Aboriginal peoples in Canada|Aboriginal]] || 98,565|| {{Percentage | 98565| 2715000 | 1}}\n|-\n| [[Middle East|Middle Eastern]] || 63,300|| {{Percentage | 63300| 2715000 | 1}}\n|-\n| [[Latin American Canadians|Latin American]] || 36,855|| {{Percentage | 36855| 2715000 | 1}}\n|-\n| [[Black Canadians|Black]] || 32,325|| {{Percentage | 32325| 2715000 | 1}}\n|-\n| Other || 43,295|| {{Percentage | 43295| 2715000 | 1}}\n|-\n|- style=\"background:#efefef; font-weight:bold\"\n| colspan=2 | Total population || 2,715,000 || {{Percentage | 2715000 | 2715000 | 1}}\n|}\n\n===Language===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"float:left; clear:left; margin-right:1em\"\n|+ Knowledge of Language (2016)<ref>[https://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2016/dp-pd/prof/details/page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=CD&Code1=5909&Geo2=PR&Code2=59&SearchText=fraser+valley&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&B1=Language&TABID=1&type=0 Census Profile, 2016 Census: Fraser Valley, Regional district]. Statistics Canada. Retrieved 16 April 2020.</ref><ref>[https://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2016/dp-pd/prof/details/page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=CMACA&Code1=933&Geo2=PR&Code2=59&SearchText=vancouver&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&B1=Language&TABID=1&type=0 Census Profile, 2016 Census